  "answer": "The corpus contains wine and intoxication mentions across 16 works. Here is a full breakdown by work:\n\n**Diwan-E-Ghalib** (mirza-ghalib-diwan-e-ghalib-74ed4c): The most extensive coverage — wine, tavern (kharabaat), the Saaqi (wine-bearer), drunkenness, and intoxication appear across dozens of chapters including ch.2, 6, 7, 14, 20, 21, 35, 42, 50, 51, 58, 59, 61, 62, 68, 70, 75, 77, 78, 100, 105, 124, 128, 131, 132, 134, 138, 146, 150, 151, 155, 169, 176, 181, 188, 190, 194, 198, 202, 239. Wine here functions as a Sufi metaphor for divine love alongside literal references.\n\n**Bang-E-Dara Part 1** (allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-1-55b25c): ch.4, 5, 9, 17, 18, 23, 25, 28, 32, 36, 40, 43, 44.\n\n**Bang-E-Dara Part 2** (allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-2-9bc58c): ch.3, 4, 5, 8, 11, 14, 16, 26, 28.\n\n**Bang-E-Dara Part 3** (allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-3-cc61e8): ch.4, 7, 11, 18, 20.\n\n**Diwan-E-Zauq** (sheikh-ibrahim-zauq-diwan-e-zauq-0fa798): ch.4, 15, 38, 45, 56, 57.\n\n**Andreas** (cynewulf-andreas-07b573): ch.1 — 'hallowed wine from water' (miracle), 'wine-halls wasted', 'wine-city', 'mead-pouring sorrow', 'heathens slept, drunk on their blood'.\n\n**Old English Elegies** (unknown-old-english-elegies-d5fe9e): ch.1 (mead-hall thane), ch.2 ('mead-bench, ale-soaked warrior, wine-sated man, mead-mad man'), ch.5 ('sipping of mead'), ch.6 ('mead-giving'), ch.7 ('mead-hall'), ch.8 ('mead-halls'; 'mead-joys'), ch.11, 14, 16 (mead-hall).\n\n**Elene** (cynewulf-elene-d2d132): ch.1 — 'in the mead-hall he received treasures'.\n\n**Manusmṛti** (unknown-manusmrti-347b76): ch.7 — 'intoxication' listed among the tenfold vices of kings.\n\n**Parāśara Smṛti** (unknown-parasara-smrti-2259be): ch.10 — woman 'overcome by intoxication or delusion'.\n\n**Slokantara** (unknown-slokantara-d7a628): ch.1 — three causes of intoxication: sura (palm wine), learning, and wealth.\n\n**Vratisasana** (unknown-vratisasana-d0fe75): ch.1 — extensive: intoxication as a moral failure ('fr